<DOC><DOCNO> AP880329-0057 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0613EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-StormsRdp     03-29 0350</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Storms Rdp,0365</SECOND><HEAD>Tornadoes, Hail Hit Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Spring thunderstorms spawned tornadoes and pounded Oklahoma withhail and winds gusting to 75 mph that destroyed a mobile home,killing a woman, while in Utah a snowstorm was blamed for a fatalcar-train collision.   Frigid air followed the storm that hit Utah on Monday, and theNational Weather Service warned fruit farmers the low temperaturescould hurt crops today.   Thunderstorms swept through central, eastern and southwesternOklahoma on Monday.   A tornado touched down in southwest Oklahoma City, andunconfirmed tornadoes were reported in nearby Mustang, Harrah andMidwest City. Another touched down just northwest of Little Rock,Ark.   In Oklahoma City, high winds destroyed a mobile home in theSherwood Homes trailer park, said authorities, who could notconfirm reports of a tornado.   Lillian Robinson, 69, was dead on arrival at Midwest CityHospital, an unidentified spokesman said. Her husband, who was notidentified, was hospitalized in serious condition.   The wind shoved some mobile homes off their foundations andshook others, said trailer park resident Mike McFarland.   ``It was a very loud noise,'' McFarland said.   High winds also threw half a dozen trailers onto their sides ata trailer company in Oklahoma City, and damaged roofs on city hall,a fast food restaurant and a funeral home in Mustang, officialssaid.   Hail up to 4 inches in diameter was reported around the state,the weather service said.   To the north, thunderstorms dropped golf ball-size hail justwest of Quincy, Ill., and marble-size hail at Leavenworth, Kan.   The Utah snowstorm caused about 50 accidents, most of themfender benders, the state Highway Patrol reported.   At the height of the storm, a freight train collided with a car,killing driver Villiami S. Pauni, 39, said Salt Lake CountySheriff's Cpl. Ron Little. The train engineer sounded his horn andthe crossing signal was working, but the car apparently slid intothe train's path, Little said.   A snowstorm in central Colorado also left roads icy, triggeringnumerous accidents. In Montana, a snow storm left up to a foot ofsnow.</TEXT></DOC>